            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Ryan Santos\u2019s story is not one of dramatic upheaval, but of quiet observation and steady ascent. Raised in Portland, Oregon, by a high school history teacher and a dental hygienist, his childhood was comfortable, middle-class, and instilled with a sense of practical curiosity. He wasn\u2019t the kid building robots; he was the one asking why his friends preferred one video game controller over another, meticulously analyzing the unspoken rules of the playground. This fascination with the \u201cwhy\u201d behind human choices led him to UC Santa Cruz, where he discovered the field of Cognitive Science, a perfect marriage of his interests in psychology and technology.\n\nHis key turning point came during his senior year. While helping his grandfather navigate a frustratingly complex medical patient portal, Ryan had an epiphany. The problem wasn\u2019t his grandfather; it was the design. That moment crystallized his career path. After graduating, he moved to San Francisco in 2011, drawn by the siren call of the tech boom. He started as a junior researcher, meticulously logging user feedback and gradually building a reputation for his empathetic, data-driven insights. Now, as a Senior UX Researcher for a large information services company in SoMa, he\u2019s the person who ensures technology serves human intuition, not the other way around.\n\nToday, Ryan lives in a bright, airy one-bedroom apartment in the Mission District with his long-term partner, Chloe, a landscape architect. His daily routine is a testament to his life\u2019s integration with the city. He catches the J Church Muni line for his 2.8-mile commute, using the time to people-watch and decompress. He\u2019s a regular at his local coffee shop, knows the owners of the corner grocer, and spends weekends with Chloe biking through Golden Gate Park or trying new restaurants in their neighborhood.\n\nWhile financially secure, Ryan feels a growing desire to apply his skills to more than just corporate products. His dream is to eventually transition into civic tech or start a small consultancy that helps non-profits and educational institutions design better, more accessible digital tools. He wants to take the empathy he honed in the corporate world and use it to solve problems like the one his grandfather faced years ago, bringing his San Francisco story full circle."
